01:57:36.884 --> 01:57:38.177
<i>They'll take any suffering</i>

01:57:38.302 --> 01:57:40.138
if they can just be in charge
of their destiny

01:57:40.304 --> 01:57:42.306
and not have it
in somebody else's hands.

01:57:42.432 --> 01:57:47.520
<i>Apple's stock has been
volatile on rumors about Jobs's health.</i>

01:57:47.645 --> 01:57:49.856
The company's stock
was halted for a time,

01:57:49.981 --> 01:57:53.693
then took a big hit when it re-opened
in after-hours trading.

01:57:53.818 --> 01:57:55.778
<i>Apple's share prices have dropped</i>

01:57:55.903 --> 01:57:58.823
<i>with every pound
that Jobs has lost in recent months.</i>

01:58:00.199 --> 01:58:02.660
<i>Apple really landed
into a dicey situation</i>

01:58:02.785 --> 01:58:04.620
<i>when Steve decided
to issue a letter saying,</i>

01:58:04.746 --> 01:58:06.622
<i>"Well, you know,
nothing's wrong with me."</i>

01:58:06.748 --> 01:58:09.250
"It's just a minor problem,"
And it wasn't a minor problem.

01:58:10.668 --> 01:58:14.172
<i>Steve Jobs made a point
of withholding from the world</i>

01:58:14.338 --> 01:58:16.799
<i>that he faced this illness.</i>

01:58:16.924 --> 01:58:18.718
<i>That's something
investors want to know,</i>

01:58:18.843 --> 01:58:20.553
<i>because when you
bought Apple stock then,</i>

01:58:20.720 --> 01:58:22.638
you were buying into Steve Jobs.

01:58:22.805 --> 01:58:26.225
He was obligated
to tell shareholders right away

01:58:26.350 --> 01:58:27.852
about this serious illness.

01:58:29.020 --> 01:58:31.731
<i>You do personally
want to give Steve the privacy,</i>

01:58:31.856 --> 01:58:34.817
<i>but Steve put the spotlight on him,</i>

01:58:34.942 --> 01:58:38.738
and you can't turn that off
just because it's inconvenient.

01:58:41.616 --> 01:58:44.368
<i>After the story came out,
I saw Steve.</i>

01:58:44.494 --> 01:58:47.079
He started talking about Apple,
and he said,

01:58:47.205 --> 01:58:51.459
<i>"You know, Apple is really a company
that doesn't have any divisions."</i>

01:58:51.584 --> 01:58:53.711
<i>"We don't have all this bureaucracy."</i>

01:58:53.836 --> 01:58:56.756
And I said, "Steve, that would be
a great story for <i>Fortune."</i>

01:58:56.881 --> 01:59:02.512
And he looked at me, and he said,
"No."

01:59:02.637 --> 01:59:08.392
"I don't think we can do that story
with you. Not now."

01:59:09.977 --> 01:59:11.604
"Not now."

01:59:11.813 --> 01:59:15.733
And then he said,
and the whole room went quiet,

01:59:15.858 --> 01:59:19.821
and he said, "you know, we used to..."

01:59:21.155 --> 01:59:24.700
"We used to really be friends
with <i>Fortune,</i>

01:59:24.826 --> 01:59:31.791
I used to be friends with <i>Fortune,</i>
but not anymore. Not anymore."

01:59:31.916 --> 01:59:35.461
And then I remember these tears
came out of his eyes,

01:59:35.586 --> 01:59:37.046
and one was on his glasses,

01:59:37.171 --> 01:59:41.676
and then one, I remember it rolling
off his cheek and hitting his shirt,

01:59:41.801 --> 01:59:46.848
and he was just crying,
and the whole room was silent.

01:59:48.891 --> 01:59:52.603
Apple CEO Steve Jobs today
made his first public appearance

01:59:52.728 --> 01:59:54.605
since getting a new liver
five months ago.

01:59:54.730 --> 01:59:55.857
<i>For the first time,</i>

01:59:55.982 --> 01:59:58.901
<i>the 54-year-old CEO
publicly acknowledged</i>

01:59:59.026 --> 02:00:02.488
<i>the liver transplant this spring
that saved his life.</i>

02:00:02.613 --> 02:00:08.244
Well, I now have the liver
of a mid-20s person.

02:00:11.873 --> 02:00:16.502
I'd like to take a moment and thank
everybody in the Apple community

02:00:16.627 --> 02:00:20.840
for the heartfelt support I got, too.
It really meant a lot.

02:00:20.965 --> 02:00:25.845
And I'd also like
to especially thank Tim Cook

02:00:25.970 --> 02:00:29.682
and the entire executive team of Apple.

02:00:29.807 --> 02:00:32.226
They really rose to the occasion

02:00:32.351 --> 02:00:36.480
and ran the company very ably
in that difficult period.

02:00:36.606 --> 02:00:38.941
So, thank you, guys.
Let's give them a round of applause.

02:00:40.484 --> 02:00:42.069
<i>He loved what he did.</i>

02:00:42.194 --> 02:00:44.238
I do have an e-mail from him
saying that.

02:00:44.363 --> 02:00:46.866
<i>He said, you know,
"Both of us were fortunate," he said,</i>

02:00:46.991 --> 02:00:49.368
<i>in that we loved what we did</i>

02:00:49.535 --> 02:00:52.288
<i>and we were able to do it
for a long time.</i>

02:00:52.413 --> 02:00:54.832
<i>And he said,
"What else could you ask for?"</i>

02:00:56.208 --> 02:01:00.922
We're maybe a little more experienced,
certainly more beat-up,

02:01:01.047 --> 02:01:04.759
but the core values are the same.

02:01:04.884 --> 02:01:09.513
I don't see why you have to change
if you get big.

02:01:09.680 --> 02:01:11.891
<i>Straightforward to me.</i>

02:01:12.016 --> 02:01:14.352
<i>Apple was big.</i>

02:01:14.518 --> 02:01:18.814
<i>By this time, one of the biggest
corporations in the world.</i>

02:01:21.275 --> 02:01:24.862
<i>But each time we saw Jobs,
he seemed smaller.</i>

02:01:28.366 --> 02:01:32.286
<i>As his devices got stronger,
Jobs got weaker.</i>

02:01:32.411 --> 02:01:35.915
It's so much more intimate
than a laptop,

02:01:36.040 --> 02:01:39.293
and it's so much more capable
than a smartphone

02:01:39.418 --> 02:01:41.253
with this gorgeous, large display.

02:01:41.379 --> 02:01:45.174
<i>I think that a lot of the grief
at Jobs's death</i>

02:01:45.299 --> 02:01:50.471
was a fear that we had been
very comfortable

02:01:50.638 --> 02:01:52.974
<i>for the last decade in his hands.</i>

02:01:53.099 --> 02:01:57.770
It's phenomenal to hold the internet
in your hand.

02:01:57.895 --> 02:02:00.189
<i>That he was going to keep
doing these amazing things.</i>

02:02:00.314 --> 02:02:04.276
Now he's gone, and there's no indication
that anyone's going to replace him.

02:02:36.976 --> 02:02:38.728
Welcome.

02:02:44.692 --> 02:02:46.068
Thank you.

02:02:58.456 --> 02:03:00.166
Thank you very much.

02:03:03.961 --> 02:03:05.546
- It always helps...
- We love you!

02:03:05.713 --> 02:03:09.300
Thank you.

02:03:09.508 --> 02:03:12.803
It always helps,
and I appreciate it very much.

02:03:12.928 --> 02:03:16.849
<i>He resigned officially
in August. Two weeks earlier,</i>

02:03:16.974 --> 02:03:20.478
<i>Apple had become the highest-valued
corporation on Earth.</i>

02:03:20.644 --> 02:03:22.271
And thank you for coming so much.

02:03:22.396 --> 02:03:24.982
<i>We've got a great week
planned for you.</i>

02:03:49.924 --> 02:03:52.927
<i>This is a field
where one does not write a principia</i>

02:03:53.052 --> 02:03:55.638
<i>which holds up for 200 years</i>

02:03:55.763 --> 02:03:58.099
<i>or paints a painting that'll be
looked at for centuries,</i>

02:03:58.224 --> 02:04:01.936
<i>or builds a church
that will be admired</i>

02:04:02.061 --> 02:04:03.979
<i>and looked at in astonishment
for centuries.</i>

02:04:04.105 --> 02:04:06.440
No, this is a field
where one does one's work,

02:04:06.565 --> 02:04:08.484
and in ten years, it's obsolete

02:04:08.609 --> 02:04:11.237
and really will not be useable
within ten or 20 years.

02:04:11.362 --> 02:04:13.280
I mean, you can't go back
and use an Apple I,

02:04:13.405 --> 02:04:14.573
cos there's no software for it.

02:04:14.740 --> 02:04:17.201
In another ten years or so,
you won't be able to use an Apple II.

02:04:17.326 --> 02:04:19.787
You won't even be able to fire it up
and see what it was like.

02:04:21.539 --> 02:04:25.000
<i>It's sort of like
sediment of rocks.</i>

02:04:25.126 --> 02:04:26.836
<i>You're building up a mountain,</i>

02:04:26.961 --> 02:04:30.131
<i>and you get to contribute
your little layer of sedimentary rock</i>

02:04:30.256 --> 02:04:32.258
<i>to make the mountain that much higher.</i>

02:04:32.383 --> 02:04:35.970
<i>But no one on the surface will,
unless they have x-ray vision,</i>

02:04:36.137 --> 02:04:37.847
<i>will see your sediment.</i>

02:04:41.267 --> 02:04:44.687
<i>In Japan, there's
an idea called "mono no aware,"</i>

02:04:44.812 --> 02:04:48.149
<i>meaning "the deep awareness of things".</i>

02:04:48.274 --> 02:04:51.235
<i>It celebrates the melancholy
of the passing of life</i>

02:04:51.360 --> 02:04:55.156
<i>and sees more beauty in the fallen leaf
than the one on the branch.</i>

02:04:56.407 --> 02:04:59.326
<i>Maybe that's what Japan held for Jobs.</i>

02:04:59.451 --> 02:05:04.331
<i>The sadness of the soul
as expressed in the beauty of things.</i>

02:05:09.253 --> 02:05:11.881
<i>In the end, I was left
with the same question</i>

02:05:12.006 --> 02:05:13.549
<i>with which I began this journey.</i>

02:05:13.674 --> 02:05:18.220
<i>"Why did so many strangers weep
for Steve Jobs?"</i>

02:05:18.345 --> 02:05:21.640
<i>It's too simple to say it was
because he gave us products we love</i>

02:05:21.807 --> 02:05:25.686
<i>without asking why we love them
the way we do.</i>

02:05:25.853 --> 02:05:28.063
<i>It's too simple even to conclude
that we love them</i>

02:05:28.230 --> 02:05:30.357
<i>because they connect us
to a wider world</i>

02:05:30.482 --> 02:05:33.611
<i>and the people in our lives
that are far away,</i>

02:05:33.777 --> 02:05:37.114
<i>because these machines isolate us, too.</i>

02:05:39.700 --> 02:05:43.579
<i>Perhaps the contradictory nature
of our experience with these gadgets</i>

02:05:43.704 --> 02:05:46.290
<i>mirrors the contradictions
in Jobs himself.</i>

02:05:48.667 --> 02:05:52.713
<i>He was an artist who sought perfection,
but could never find peace.</i>

02:05:54.965 --> 02:05:58.844
<i>He had the focus of a monk,
but none of the empathy.</i>

02:06:01.096 --> 02:06:04.808
<i>He offered us freedom,
but only within a closed garden,</i>

02:06:04.934 --> 02:06:07.061
<i>to which he held the key.</i>

02:06:11.315 --> 02:06:13.317
<i>To reconcile these contradictions,</i>

02:06:13.442 --> 02:06:17.196
<i>I think we have to look to the other
half of our relationship with Jobs.</i>

02:06:17.321 --> 02:06:18.989
<i>To ourselves.</i>

02:06:22.243 --> 02:06:26.455
<i>As Jobs wanted it,
the screen of my iPhone is dark.</i>

02:06:26.622 --> 02:06:29.208
<i>A Zen landscape of the unseen.</i>

02:06:29.333 --> 02:06:34.296
<i>If I stare into it, I see
an obscure reflection of myself,</i>

02:06:34.421 --> 02:06:37.049
<i>but this impression
lasts just a fleeting moment</i>

02:06:37.174 --> 02:06:40.761
<i>before I press the home key
and the screen lights up.</i>

02:06:40.928 --> 02:06:44.765
<i>But perhaps I should spend a moment
regarding that reflection,</i>

02:06:44.932 --> 02:06:50.938
<i>asking myself what, in buying
and using this product, I am doing?</i>

02:06:51.063 --> 02:06:53.565
<i>What is the full nature
of my transaction</i>

02:06:53.732 --> 02:06:58.153
<i>with the maker of this magical
and intimate machine?</i>

